        "id": 2080521,
        "name": "Gary Schulte",
        "username": "Gary_Schulte",
        "avatar_template": "/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/g/f08c70/{size}.png",
        "created_at": "2016-12-17T18:41:18.000Z",
        "cooked": "<p>I was a big fan of the quality, dryness, and acidity of the Thibaud Boudignon 2012 chenin blancs. Based on that, and a few notes I had seen on French wine sites, I purchased a mixed case of 2013s. About a year ago I opened a 2013 TB Anjou Blanc and it was too acidic and almost undrinkable. Not thinking too much of it I  figured I would let the wines rest and see what would come out of them. Well with a little impatience on my part I opened another TB 2013 Anjou Blanc this past week to have with clam(just pulled from the ocean) linguine.  Well this wine has light aromatics that I would not describe as chenin like. The wine is slightly yellow in color. On the mouth this wine is only slightly better than before and is dominated by sourness with very little fruit flavors coming through in what I would call tart apple-lemon. After thinking about this the wine comes of as having too much malic acid which I take to be harvested too early and/or pressed too hard. The yellow color could be a result of the hard pressing, slight rot in the grapes, or a touch of oak color in the wine. In reflecting on the Loire harvest that year there was clearly a problem with late flowering(cool Spring) and thus late harvesting(mid Oct) and quantities were down in some areas because of hail damage in June. So my overall assessment is that the Anjou Blanc from 2013 may never come around. I do not think their is enough fruit to wait for the taming of acid as we are talking geologic time for the latter. At this point I\u2019m letting the Boudignon Savennieres and a\u2019 Francoise cuvee wines stay in a long sleep. I might Coravin one of each in about about 2 years time.</p>",
        "post_number": 1,
        "post_type": 1,
        "posts_count": 2,
